<li id="cite_note-63"><b><a href="#cite_ref-63" title="">^</a></b> <i><a href="/wiki/Aesop%27s_Fables" title="Aesop's Fables">Aesop's Fables</a></i>, repeatedly rendered in both verse and prose since first being recorded about 500 B.C., are perhaps the richest single source of allegorical poetry through the ages. Other notables examples include the <i><a href="/wiki/Roman_de_la_Rose" title="Roman de la Rose">Roman de la Rose</a></i>, a 13th-century French poem, <a href="/wiki/William_Langland" title="William Langland">William Langland</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Piers_Ploughman" title="Piers Ploughman" class="mw-redirect">Piers Ploughman</a></i> in the 14th century, and <a href="/wiki/Jean_de_la_Fontaine" title="Jean de la Fontaine" class="mw-redirect">Jean de la Fontaine</a>'s <i>Fables</i> (influenced by Aesop's) in the 17th century (available in French on wikisource).<a href="http://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/Fables_de_La_Fontaine" class="external autonumber" title="http://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/Fables_de_La_Fontaine" rel="nofollow">[9]</a>.</li>
